- VSCode Version: 1.3.0-Insider (2016-07-01 build)
- OS Version: Windows 7

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Open a new buffer;
2. Type three lines of text;
3. Open the find and replace dialogue and turn on regex;
4. In the Find field, input \n; in the Replace with field, input a whitespace;
5. Hit replace all.

The whitespace is supposed to replace the newline character entirely, but it seems the newline character is retained --- whatever is replacing \n got appended to each of the matching newline.

**Problem:**

Currently, VSCode doesn't display version information about languages that are used by extensions, so you have no way to know **what** is the current language version that the extension is using and **whether** the extension was tested with version 1.0, 2.0 or whatever of the language, you have to assume that the extension just works, VSCode itself doesn't even report information about TypeScript.

For example, if I want to know what version of TypeScript ships with VSCode I have to read the release docs which I do but this isn't the point and if I upgrade or downgrade I have to assume VSCode is using whatever version of TypeScript I set it up with but I have no feedback about the version the editor consumes either because the information is not exposed to the UI or not available at all.

_In fact, it's odd that when you type `ext` to tasks in VSCode, VSCode tells you `no extensions found` but it actually uses many extensions under the hood, it's okay to prevent people from removing them but it should certainly allow you to list them but that's probably another issue._

_**Solution:**_

I didn't have the time or the chance to write an extension _yet_ so I don't know the infrastructure of VSCode so I really don't know whether something like this exists but it would be really great if VSCode had an API that authors could implement to get the version of the language they consume.

Something like this:

```
class SomeLanguageExtension {
    get currentLanguageVersion(): string {
        return SomeExternalService();
    }
}
```

Then VSCode would have the ability to take advantage of this to display the version in the UI next to where you pick the language.

What would be even better is something like this:

```
class SomeLanguageExtension {
    get currentLanguageVersion(): string {
        return SomeExternalService(); // Shouldn't be hardcoded.
    }

    get supportedLanguageVersions(): string {
        return ["2.x", "3.0", "6.x"]; // Hardcoded.
    }
}
```

As far as I know an extension manager is planned for VSCode so the `supportedLanguageVersions` API can be used to tell users what are the versions of a language that the extension supports or tested against.

Having no API for this or not exposing this to the UI means authors are left to write it as part of their extension page or somewhere else or not at all and users need to look for it or ask the author that may or may not answer you, in short all I'm saying is this information needs to be transparent and crystal clear. :)

@bpasero thoughts on this? I'd like to give this a shot at some point if everyone is cool with it. The reasons for doing so are:
- [libsass](https://www.npmjs.com/package/node-sass) is very mature and on par with the original ruby lib in terms of features
- Significantly reduce the size and complexity of our development css files through leveraging nesting, for example this:

  ``` css
  .monaco-workbench .panel.integrated-terminal .xterm {
    background-color: transparent!important;
    position: relative;
  }

  .monaco-workbench .panel.integrated-terminal .xterm:focus {
    outline: none;
  }

  .hc-black .monaco-workbench .panel.integrated-terminal .xterm:focus {
    outline: 2px solid #f38518;
  }
  ```

  becomes:

  ``` scss
  // In a shared file
  $hc-outline-color: #f38518;

  .monaco-workbench .panel.integrated-terminal .xterm {
    background-color: transparent!important;
    position: relative;

    &:focus {
        outline: none;

        .hc-black & {
            outline: 2px solid $hc-outline-color;
        }
    }
  }
  ```
- We could leverage Sass variables (compile time) for non-themeable colors in addition to CSS variables for themeable colors (#8151). Sass variables can also be used for reusable images, media queries, margins, etc.
- Use of `//` comments are not included in compiled CSS, meaning we can add more documentation to complex styles without worrying about it ending up in the resulting file
- Mixins for commonly used styles/media queries/etc.
- It's way more fun to write in Sass

/cc @bgashler1
